{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656499"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:15:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0,0.96,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77312"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62819"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10165"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26573"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77312"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELangerhans cells are specialised immune cells found within the epidermis of the skin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of Langerhans cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generate new epidermal cells","Synthesise keratin proteins","Secrete sebum","Present antigens to T lymphocytes","Produce melanin pigment"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELangerhans cells \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent antigens to T lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E as their primary function. They are dendritic cells that capture, process and present foreign antigens to T cells in lymph nodes, initiating immune responses against skin pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduce melanin pigment\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of melanocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesise keratin proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by keratinocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate new epidermal cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs through division of basal keratinocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecrete sebum\u003C/strong\u003E - This is produced by sebaceous glands\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELangerhans cells form a network throughout the epidermis where they constantly sample the local environment for potential pathogens. Upon encountering foreign antigens, they migrate to regional lymph nodes to activate T cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Langerhans cells are dendritic cells found in the epidermis that present antigens to T lymphocytes.","Langerhans cells originate from bone marrow and migrate to the epidermis during development.","The primary function of Langerhans cells is immune surveillance and antigen presentation in skin."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62819"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62819"},"att